Dividing the first three nonzero terms in the Taylor series for $\sin x$
by $x$,

\begin{align*}
\frac{\sin x}{x} \approx 1 - \frac{x^2}{3!} + \frac{x^4}{5!} .
\end{align*}

Hence,

\begin{align*} 
\int_0^1 \frac{\sin x}{x}\,dx &\approx \int_0^1\left(1 - \frac{x^2}{3!} + \frac{x^4}{5!}\right)\, dx\\
& = \left. x  - \frac{x^3}{3\cdot3!} + \frac{x^5}{5\cdot5!}\right|_0^1\\
&= 1  - \frac{1}{18} + \frac{1}{5\cdot 120}= 1  - \frac{1}{18} + \frac{1}{600} =  \frac{1800-100+3}{1800} = \frac{1703}{1800} .
\end{align*}

\emph{(Note that this is a pretty good approximation.
$\frac{1703}{1800} \approx 0.946111,$ while WolframAlpha approximates
the full integral $\int_0^1 \frac{\sin x}{x}\,dx$ with $0.946083$.)}
